The paper describes a robotic system developed for providing mobile grasping assistance for activities of daily living (ADLs) for people with motor disabilities. The system uses grasp detection algorithms to allow previously unseen objects to be picked up by the system, and the algorithms also allow for objects to be grasped in cluttered environments. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, as it involves the development of a robotic system. Additionally, the use of grasp detection algorithms suggests that the paper could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of a user interface with a variety of access methods for selecting desired objects, which suggests that it could belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of laser selection, which suggests that it could belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates the system in a number of experiments, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
